Description of the data ¶

Volume: is the total amount of trading activity

Open Price : The Stock at which opens at the start of market

High price : The particular stock which made high during that particular day

Low Price : The Particular stock which made Low during that particular day

Close Price : The stock closing at the end of the Market hour

Adusted closing price: The adjusted closing price amends a stock's closing price to reflect that stock's value after accounting for any corporate actions (like Adjusting Prices for Stock Splits, Adjusting for Dividends, Adjusting for Rights Offerings)

Reference: https://www.investopedia.com/terms/a/adjusted_closing_price.asp
https://www.quora.com/What-is-an-open-high-low-close-price-in-stock-trading

In this project, the analysis involves utilising stock opening prices for the purpose of pattern detection and prediction.

# Reference: https://machinelearningmastery.com/how-to-develop-lstm-models-for-time-series-forecasting/
# Reference: https://machinelearningmastery.com/time-series-prediction-lstm-recurrent-neural-networks-python-keras/

# convert an array of values into a dataset matrix
def create_dataset(dataset, time_step):
    dataX, dataY = [], []
    for i in range(len(dataset)-time_step-1):
        a = dataset[i:(i+time_step), 0]   ###i=0, 0,1,2,3-----99   100 
        dataX.append(a)
        dataY.append(dataset[i + time_step, 0])
    return np.array(dataX), np.array(dataY)

# create simple RNN model
model_simplernn = Sequential([
    SimpleRNN(units = 50, activation= 'tanh', return_sequences= True, input_shape= (X_train.shape[1],X_train.shape[2])),
    Dropout(0.2),
    SimpleRNN(units = 50, activation= 'tanh', return_sequences= True),
    Dropout(0.2),
    SimpleRNN(units = 50, activation= 'tanh', return_sequences= True),
    Dropout(0.2),
    SimpleRNN(units = 50),
    Dense(units=1)
])

# Function to make Predictions, calculate RMSE and plotting

def predict_and_rmse(model, scaled_X_train, scaled_X_test, scaled_y_train, scaled_y_test, plot_title):

    #Make the predictions using the model
    train_predict = model.predict(scaled_X_train)
    test_predict = model.predict(scaled_X_test)
         
    #Inverse transform the predictions
    train_predict_inv_transf = scaler.inverse_transform(train_predict)
    test_predict_inv_transf = scaler.inverse_transform(test_predict)
    
    #Inverse transform scaled_y_train and scaled_y_test
    y_train_inv_transf = scaler.inverse_transform(scaled_y_train.reshape(-1,1))
    y_test_inv_transf = scaler.inverse_transform(scaled_y_test.reshape(-1,1))
    
    # calculate root mean squared error
    rmse_trainscore = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_train_inv_transf[:,0], train_predict_inv_transf[:,0]))
    print('Train Score: %.2f RMSE' % (rmse_trainscore))
    rmse_testscore = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_inv_transf[:,0], test_predict_inv_transf[:,0]))
    print('Test Score: %.2f RMSE' % (rmse_testscore))
    
    # shift train predictions for plotting
    train_predict_plot_df = np.empty(shape = df_f_scaled.shape)
    train_predict_plot_df[:,:] =np.nan
    train_predict_plot_df[time_step : len(train_predict_inv_transf) + time_step,:] = train_predict_inv_transf

    # shift test predictions for plotting
    test_predict_plot_df = np.empty(shape = df_f_scaled.shape)
    test_predict_plot_df[:,:] =np.nan
    test_predict_plot_df[len(train_predict_inv_transf) + time_step+ time_step + 1 : len(df_f_scaled)-1 ,:] = test_predict_inv_transf

    # plot baseline and predictions
    plt.figure(figsize=(12,3))
    plt.plot(df_f['Open'],'r',label = 'Baseline data')
    plt.plot(train_predict_plot_df,'b',label = 'train_prediction')
    plt.plot(test_predict_plot_df,'g',label = 'test_prediction')
    plt.ylabel("Share price (Rs)")
    plt.xlabel("Days - From June 2012 to June 2023")
    plt.title(plot_title)
    plt.legend()
     
    return train_predict_inv_transf, test_predict_inv_transf, rmse_trainscore, rmse_testscore

# Function to define the LSTM model search space
def build_model(hp):
    model_lstm_hp = Sequential()
    model_lstm_hp.add(LSTM(hp.Int('lstm_1_units', min_value=32,max_value=128,step=32),return_sequences=True, activation = 'tanh', input_shape=(X_train.shape[1],X_train.shape[2])))
    model_lstm_hp.add(Dropout(hp.Float('Dropout_rate_1',min_value=0,max_value=0.4,step=0.1)))
    model_lstm_hp.add(LSTM(hp.Int('lstm_2_units', min_value=32,max_value=128,step=32),return_sequences=True, activation = 'tanh'))
    model_lstm_hp.add(Dropout(hp.Float('Dropout_rate_2',min_value=0,max_value=0.4,step=0.1)))
    model_lstm_hp.add(LSTM(hp.Int('lstm_3_units', min_value=32,max_value=128,step=32),return_sequences=True, activation = 'tanh'))
    model_lstm_hp.add(Dropout(hp.Float('Dropout_rate_3',min_value=0,max_value=0.4,step=0.1)))
    model_lstm_hp.add(LSTM(hp.Int('lstm_4_units', min_value=32,max_value=128,step=32), activation = 'tanh'))
    model_lstm_hp.add(Dense(units = 1))
    model_lstm_hp.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mean_squared_error', metrics=['mse'])
    
#    model_lstm_hp.compile(

#        metrics=['mse']
#    )
    return model_lstm_hp
